    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the advice. i tried valgrind but we're on bare metal so i can't really run that. i don't have a lot of overhead for fancy profilers either. can you suggest some low-level ways to track allocations manually, like maybe overriding the new/delete operators or something similar? i need to know which specific modules are eating the heap over time.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, you can absolutely track allocations manually on bare metal by overriding the `new` and `delete` operators, but you'll need to be very careful to avoid creating a new leak while trying to find the old one. Since you're on embedded C++, you can wrap your heap manager to log every allocation and deallocation, storing the function name and line number where the memory was requested. This is similar to how a goblin keeps a ledger of every coin it steals and every coin it returns, so you can audit the accounts later.\n\nHere's a basic approach:\n\n1.  **Create a custom allocator class** that wraps your existing heap manager.\n2.  **Override `operator new` and `operator delete`** to intercept every allocation and deallocation.\n3.  **Log the details** (function name, line number, size) to a circular buffer or a non-volatile flash memory area, since you can't rely on the heap for logging.\n4.  **Use a static counter** to track the total number of allocations and deallocations for each module.\n\nThis way, you can generate a report at the end of the system run or periodically during operation to see which modules are consuming",
      "source": "target",
